WEBVTT

00:00:32.047 --> 00:00:33.285
<v Ahmed Kabir Chaion> Hello everyone.

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:37.475
Once again, welcome to WordPress
Accessibility Day 2020.

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:39.789
My name is Ahmed Kabir Chaion

00:00:39.814 --> 00:00:42.479
and I'm working as a Business Development
Manager at weDevs.

00:00:42.504 --> 00:00:46.802
I'm also a regular contributor to making
WordPress documentation,

00:00:46.827 --> 00:00:50.064
design, polyglots, accessibility, hosting
community,

00:00:50.089 --> 00:00:52.121
Learn WordPress and marketing teams.

00:00:52.272 --> 00:00:54.320
I will be your host for this session.

00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:58.600
You're here for the 9 a.m. UTC talk with
Mitchell Evan.

00:00:59.119 --> 00:01:02.592
Please feel free to add your questions to
the YouTube chat feed

00:01:02.617 --> 00:01:04.359
and we'll answer those at the end.

00:01:04.920 --> 00:01:08.189
So, when selecting a
content management system,

00:01:08.214 --> 00:01:11.959
you're already asking,
can it produce an accessible website?

00:01:12.599 --> 00:01:15.959
But a simple yes to that question is not
always enough.

00:01:16.319 --> 00:01:20.350
In this presentation, you will learn how
to ask more detailed questions

00:01:20.375 --> 00:01:23.388
to find out the reality behind
accessibility claims.

00:01:23.799 --> 00:01:25.719
This talk focuses on the following.

00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:29.359
How to use accessibility standards for
authoring tools

00:01:29.359 --> 00:01:35.250
to help answer the detailed question
WCAG 2.0 and 2.1,

00:01:35.282 --> 00:01:39.287
the US and EU public procurement
standards, ATAG,

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:42.319
the importance of the prompts requirement.

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:46.040
How to read a VPAT report skeptically.

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:49.735
What to look for in a trustworthy
accessibility report.

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:54.079
ATAG's unique extra conformance
requirements.

00:01:54.535 --> 00:01:57.758
Why we should treat ATAG as required,

00:01:57.783 --> 00:02:01.560
even when it's not explicitly listed in
policy.

00:02:02.439 --> 00:02:04.391
The speaker of the session, Mitchell Evan,

00:02:04.416 --> 00:02:07.760
has coached design and development teams
for nine years.

00:02:08.030 --> 00:02:13.690
Harnessing his ADHD creativity to achieve
enterprise-scale accessibility

00:02:13.724 --> 00:02:18.443
through the power of authoring tools,
UI frameworks and design systems.

00:02:18.719 --> 00:02:23.515
Most recently, he led the VPAT reporting
practice at Level Access,

00:02:23.540 --> 00:02:26.647
applying International Accessibility
Standard,

00:02:26.671 --> 00:02:32.688
WCAG 2.1, Section 508, and EN 301 549,

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:38.159
to the web application, native software,
authoring tools, and two-way communications.

00:02:38.599 --> 00:02:42.019
Mitchell recently moved
from San Francisco to Berlin

00:02:42.044 --> 00:02:45.775
to help build delightfully inclusive
technology

00:02:45.800 --> 00:02:49.039
in the new era of
European accessibility directives.

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:53.151
Which brings to the session,
if it's true, it ain't bragging,

00:02:53.175 --> 00:02:55.305
choosing a CMS for accessibility.

00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:58.080
Mitchell, welcome to WordPress
Accessibility Day.

00:02:58.199 --> 00:02:59.599
The floor is yours.

00:03:01.159 --> 00:03:03.159
<v Mitchell Evan> Thank you very much, Ahmed,
for the introduction.

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:05.658
And can you see my first title slide okay?

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:09.833
<v Ahmed> We are just waiting for your slides
to be shared.

00:03:10.516 --> 00:03:12.402
Just share the slides.
<v Mitchell> Oh, right.</v>

00:03:12.427 --> 00:03:14.640
<v Ahmed> No problem.</v>
<v Mitchell> We'll do that again.</v>

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:18.616
How about now?

00:03:18.641 --> 00:03:21.599
<v Ahmed> That worked. We can see your slides.

00:03:22.114 --> 00:03:23.907
<v Mitchell> Okay. You can see the full screen?

00:03:24.233 --> 00:03:25.294
<v Ahmed> Yes, we do.

00:03:25.319 --> 00:03:26.487
<v Mitchell> Fantastic.

00:03:26.512 --> 00:03:28.106
All right. Well, thank you, Ahmed.

00:03:28.131 --> 00:03:29.463
And welcome, folks.

00:03:29.919 --> 00:03:31.879
If it's true, it ain't bragging.

00:03:31.904 --> 00:03:35.879
Choosing a CMS, a content management
system for accessibility.

00:03:36.319 --> 00:03:38.584
As Ahmed said, my name is Mitchell Evan.

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:43.069
And I want to start by, if anybody does
not see the screen,

00:03:43.097 --> 00:03:55.365
and wants the slides,
https://bit.ly/cmsbrag.

00:03:55.770 --> 00:04:01.879
And these slides are creative commons with
some special requirements.

00:04:02.199 --> 00:04:04.662
If you want to remix and reuse them.

00:04:05.479 --> 00:04:12.039
So I'm going to start with a thought
provoking question to warm up.

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:15.549
Who chooses your content
management system?

00:04:16.639 --> 00:04:19.836
And this is a question that's going to be
answered by different people

00:04:19.861 --> 00:04:21.800
in different roles in different ways.

00:04:23.258 --> 00:04:24.519
Ponder for a moment.

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:26.399
You might be very new to content
management.

00:04:26.399 --> 00:04:29.279
You might be a core contributor to
WordPress.

00:04:29.759 --> 00:04:32.800
But who chooses the content management
system that you use?

00:04:33.504 --> 00:04:35.353
It could be a lot of different people.

00:04:35.973 --> 00:04:43.240
This session today is especially for the
content management system decision makers.

00:04:44.445 --> 00:04:45.920
But it's also for everybody.

00:04:45.959 --> 00:04:49.199
Decision makers could also be known as
buyers.

00:04:50.063 --> 00:04:55.199
Some people, you know, buy software for
their company or agency.

00:04:55.466 --> 00:04:59.680
But even if you don't spend money on it,
you're investing your time.

00:05:00.032 --> 00:05:01.752
So you're a buyer either way.

00:05:01.926 --> 00:05:03.879
You could be an IT architect.

00:05:04.319 --> 00:05:08.639
You could be a template designer and
developer.

00:05:08.942 --> 00:05:10.480
You could be a small business owner.

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:15.565
Of course, there's a huge number of people
who invest their time and energy and money

00:05:15.590 --> 00:05:19.494
into content management
systems as a small business owner.

00:05:20.327 --> 00:05:24.600
Anybody who chooses a template, you may be
given the content management system,

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:28.439
but you choose a template or install a
plugin or activate a plugin.

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:31.120
You're really modifying the content
management system.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:32.959
So you're a decision maker as well.

00:05:33.688 --> 00:05:36.439
For everybody else, let's say you're just
an author.

00:05:38.236 --> 00:05:39.839
You are an influencer.

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:44.335
You may need to influence the next
generation of content management systems.

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:49.879
If you find that the one you're using is
not up to what you need for accessibility.

00:05:49.879 --> 00:05:54.519
Now, probably a lot of people on this
call are on WordPress, which is quite good.

00:05:54.976 --> 00:05:57.616
You know, so influence what it can do.

00:06:01.639 --> 00:06:05.913
So that when you choose your current
or next content management system,

00:06:05.938 --> 00:06:09.113
it's really an investment in accessibility,

00:06:09.138 --> 00:06:11.589
investment in accessibility

00:06:13.721 --> 00:06:15.480
How to choose your CMS.

00:06:15.935 --> 00:06:17.292
Here it is in one slide.

00:06:18.319 --> 00:06:22.279
Choose WordPress.
38% of the internet can't be wrong.

00:06:22.585 --> 00:06:23.839
Isn't that right?

00:06:23.839 --> 00:06:25.759
We are all here for accessibility day.

00:06:26.210 --> 00:06:28.519
That's just a joke.
Here, I'm going to go.

00:06:28.639 --> 00:06:31.892
I'm going to go step by step
a little bit more nuanced in that.

00:06:31.932 --> 00:06:34.319
How to choose your content management
system.

00:06:34.843 --> 00:06:38.040
I'm going to say that maybe it's more like
two steps.

00:06:39.072 --> 00:06:43.398
Step one, ask what the content
management system can do,

00:06:44.033 --> 00:06:46.519
and then verify that that's true.

00:06:47.476 --> 00:06:50.157
And so, you know, the rest of this
is really going to be

00:06:50.182 --> 00:06:52.439
breaking down into those two themes.

00:06:53.531 --> 00:06:55.243
Ask and verify.

00:06:57.188 --> 00:07:00.743
Unfortunately, there's more than three
slides in this deck.

00:07:01.791 --> 00:07:07.115
Today, I believe that choosing a content
management system for accessibility

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:08.680
is harder than it should be.

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:13.480
And I'll give a couple of 
perspectives on this.

00:07:14.399 --> 00:07:20.290
This is from the EU, the European Union,
we4Authors project,

00:07:20.315 --> 00:07:22.240
which concluded this year.

00:07:23.035 --> 00:07:27.836
One of the conclusions is procurers,
that's buyers,

00:07:27.861 --> 00:07:31.233
find it difficult to validate
which company can be trusted

00:07:31.258 --> 00:07:32.839
when it comes to accessibility.

00:07:34.079 --> 00:07:41.998
And that is borne out by the fact that even
though just a week ago was the deadline

00:07:42.023 --> 00:07:46.766
for the entire EU public sector
to have all of their websites accessible.

00:07:48.352 --> 00:07:51.425
Many really haven't met that
or have met it partially,

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:54.319
With so much content built on content
management,

00:07:56.119 --> 00:07:58.542
certainly training and learning curves 
are part of that,

00:07:58.567 --> 00:08:01.923
but we have to look to the content
management systems themselves.

00:08:03.098 --> 00:08:04.680
And these gaps really matter.

00:08:04.680 --> 00:08:07.486
And I'm going to read this entire
next large quote,

00:08:07.883 --> 00:08:11.560
because I think it really sums
up the importance of getting this right.

00:08:13.163 --> 00:08:19.000
And this is from Kyle, who runs digital
accessibility for Harvard University.

00:08:19.798 --> 00:08:23.106
If making something accessible
turns into a process

00:08:23.139 --> 00:08:26.396
where you have to be a
secondary subject matter expert,

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:27.600
it's not going to happen.

00:08:28.329 --> 00:08:32.679
These faculty are brilliant at what they
do, and we need to make it easy for them

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:34.622
to share and disseminate information.

00:08:34.954 --> 00:08:38.247
Today, some of the research being
done is a matter of life and death,

00:08:38.272 --> 00:08:40.080
issues critical to society.

00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:45.345
I don't think I need to add
any more to what Kyle said.

00:08:46.155 --> 00:08:48.424
You know, that really just shows—

00:08:48.449 --> 00:08:53.479
and I should mention that Kyle
himself is a user with a visual disability.

00:08:53.504 --> 00:08:58.830
And so, you know, this perspective,
I feel like is just really—

00:08:58.855 --> 00:09:01.176
we should really pay attention
to a perspective like this

00:09:01.201 --> 00:09:03.405
and say, what can we do to make this
better?

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:12.066
Because if it's not accessible,
we want to think of it as not functional.

00:09:12.091 --> 00:09:15.106
By now, if you've watched
some of these presentations,

00:09:15.131 --> 00:09:17.639
I think people have said
different things in different ways.

00:09:18.756 --> 00:09:23.623
But, you know, I'll add
a way of looking at this is

00:09:24.220 --> 00:09:27.828
thinking of accessibility,
not as a feature or an add-on,

00:09:27.853 --> 00:09:30.511
but it's just a measure of, does it work?

00:09:30.536 --> 00:09:33.611
And of course, you want
your content to work for people.

00:09:34.527 --> 00:09:37.697
When it is accessible,
people with disabilities can use it

00:09:37.722 --> 00:09:39.460
and anybody can use it.

00:09:40.150 --> 00:09:45.819
We've seen images like this. Here's
one more of a gently rising ramp,

00:09:46.454 --> 00:09:47.954
on a beautiful hillside.

00:09:49.194 --> 00:09:50.914
It's for everybody.

00:09:54.799 --> 00:09:56.417
So those two steps:

00:09:56.441 --> 00:10:00.840
step one, asking what the content
management system can do.

00:10:02.110 --> 00:10:07.848
We're going to ask or look for, you can
ask Google your favorite search engine,

00:10:09.005 --> 00:10:11.519
ask for accessibility statements.

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:15.205
And good news—
I highlighted a couple here—

00:10:15.230 --> 00:10:17.570
WordPress has a very nicely formatted one.

00:10:18.507 --> 00:10:19.863
Drupal as well.

00:10:19.888 --> 00:10:23.759
I want to give a good
honorable mention to Wix.

00:10:23.799 --> 00:10:29.775
For those who have been following over the
years, I would say I myself used to,

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:33.725
if somebody asked me
what's a terrible system for accessibility,

00:10:33.750 --> 00:10:35.265
I would have pointed to Wix.

00:10:35.876 --> 00:10:40.630
They are really turning it around. So we
give them kind of an honorable mention

00:10:40.655 --> 00:10:45.302
and their own documentation
on accessibility is now—

00:10:45.326 --> 00:10:47.153
has really become quite good.

00:10:47.178 --> 00:10:49.519
I'll give them like a real
turnaround success story.

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:53.200
Now, again, we're not done with this
presentation.

00:10:53.225 --> 00:10:55.440
If this were the whole answer,
we could end it here.

00:10:56.350 --> 00:11:01.316
Of course we need to scrutinize these
things because nothing is 100% complete.

00:11:01.761 --> 00:11:04.519
We're going to talk about,
kind of, what to look for.

00:11:04.543 --> 00:11:08.000
You know, what is so important to
look for in these accessibility statements.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.879
And now these are general kind of pro
sorts of statements.

00:11:13.404 --> 00:11:16.000
A statement of commitment.
They always start with this:

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.732
We are committed to accessibility and
that's not worth much,

00:11:19.757 --> 00:11:22.639
but it's a public statement
self-commitment.

00:11:22.639 --> 00:11:24.040
And so we can…

00:11:25.646 --> 00:11:27.894
the fact that it's there,
it's not worthless.

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:33.879
It means we should hold that, whoever says
publicly, "I'm committed to accessibility."

00:11:33.879 --> 00:11:35.760
It tells the rest of us
to hold them to that.

00:11:36.303 --> 00:11:38.360
And what are some details that help us
do that?

00:11:39.628 --> 00:11:46.528
In the case of content management systems,
it's really important to tell users

00:11:46.553 --> 00:11:48.593
how to configure it for accessibility.

00:11:48.618 --> 00:11:52.300
You know, in the case of WordPress,
you know, accessibility-ready themes

00:11:52.325 --> 00:11:55.519
that we've heard about
accessibility-ready themes.

00:11:56.601 --> 00:12:00.950
Drupal has core modules, both have
plugins.

00:12:00.983 --> 00:12:04.047
And as we've heard plugins can
break accessibility.

00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:06.975
So really having that
information available.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.279
You know, kind of a go, no go on
accessibility with this type of stuff.

00:12:11.928 --> 00:12:20.194
The statements, should say how
they've assessed their own accessibility

00:12:20.219 --> 00:12:22.409
or better yet using a third-party audit,

00:12:22.434 --> 00:12:26.960
an independent reviewer
to say, what is accessible.

00:12:27.711 --> 00:12:29.600
There are going to be known issues.

00:12:29.630 --> 00:12:32.516
There are known issues in all of these
content management systems,

00:12:32.550 --> 00:12:34.971
and they should disclose them,
so we know what to do about—

00:12:34.996 --> 00:12:38.042
and we know what works
and what doesn't today.

00:12:38.405 --> 00:12:41.483
Hopefully some be able
to either use workarounds

00:12:41.508 --> 00:12:45.120
or really choose whether to
use that system.

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:50.269
A remediation plan,
a roadmap for what to do about it

00:12:50.294 --> 00:12:54.003
is really important when
you're ready to invest your time

00:12:54.034 --> 00:12:55.926
and or money into a new system.

00:12:56.292 --> 00:13:00.925
Okay, if it's getting there,
is it being actively worked on?

00:13:00.950 --> 00:13:02.061
and, you know,

00:13:02.092 --> 00:13:06.211
and I will say last but not least
a feedback channel for improvements.

00:13:06.742 --> 00:13:11.337
Even if a system is perfect today,
technology changes:

00:13:11.362 --> 00:13:14.968
browsers, assistive
technology, the world changes

00:13:14.992 --> 00:13:19.579
and, you know, it's not realistic
for accessibility to be bug free

00:13:19.604 --> 00:13:21.119
at every moment.

00:13:21.144 --> 00:13:22.278
We'd want that,

00:13:22.303 --> 00:13:25.501
We want every software to be
completely bug free at every moment.

00:13:25.556 --> 00:13:29.763
But users of course always find things
and not just for accessibility.

00:13:29.788 --> 00:13:33.542
And so, having a feedback channel
is a real—

00:13:33.567 --> 00:13:35.412
is also kind of a vote

00:13:35.436 --> 00:13:39.621
in favor of this organization producing
this content management system.

00:13:40.184 --> 00:13:43.388
It is actually committed to accessibility.

00:13:43.413 --> 00:13:47.519
Because if they are,
they will want to hear from users.

00:13:50.754 --> 00:13:54.102
So we talked just now
about accessibility statements.

00:13:54.135 --> 00:13:57.293
There's another thing
called a conformance report,

00:13:57.317 --> 00:13:59.208
And this really
gets into more detail.

00:14:00.447 --> 00:14:03.429
And for content management
systems specifically,

00:14:03.463 --> 00:14:06.589
you've heard from others and there's
plentiful information on the internet,

00:14:06.614 --> 00:14:10.889
but just about, you know,
content accessibility,

00:14:10.914 --> 00:14:13.874
just like is a website accessible.

00:14:14.350 --> 00:14:21.682
Content management systems have some
additional important, specific requirements.

00:14:22.524 --> 00:14:25.639
The first one may be obvious
but it's good to split it out.

00:14:25.664 --> 00:14:27.749
Allowed: Is it possible?

00:14:27.773 --> 00:14:31.513
Does the system allow the user
to create accessible content?

00:14:31.538 --> 00:14:32.888
Is that even possible?

00:14:32.912 --> 00:14:36.628
We've heard a lot about that
in these presentations.

00:14:36.653 --> 00:14:41.419
I didn't catch Hidde's presentation.
I was preparing for this one.

00:14:41.444 --> 00:14:44.968
I regret doing that. I'm going to
come back and watch that later

00:14:44.993 --> 00:14:48.084
but Hidde de Vries just presented on ATAG —

00:14:48.108 --> 00:14:50.799
the authoring tool
accessibility guidelines.

00:14:50.831 --> 00:14:53.700
And they're really going to cover
these next two.

00:14:53.725 --> 00:14:58.112
Prompting: Does the CMS
prompt and guide authors to do that,

00:14:58.137 --> 00:14:59.732
to create accessible content?

00:14:59.757 --> 00:15:05.692
Not just possible but actually encourage
and surface the features that do that,

00:15:05.717 --> 00:15:08.574
and inclusive authoring, I call it,

00:15:08.599 --> 00:15:13.945
is a summary of the various features
of the content creation process,

00:15:13.970 --> 00:15:16.177
content creation functions themselves.

00:15:16.202 --> 00:15:19.362
Can a person with disabilities use those?

00:15:19.699 --> 00:15:22.360
So these are distinct—
we're going to think about,

00:15:22.480 --> 00:15:24.060
remember these three as we go through

00:15:24.084 --> 00:15:26.786
because we're going to get
into a lot more detail on these.

00:15:28.325 --> 00:15:32.768
Now the hard way to ask, well,
what should be in these standards,

00:15:32.793 --> 00:15:37.659
in these reports, is to kind of look
at all the regulations around the world,

00:15:37.684 --> 00:15:39.779
figure out what they require.

00:15:39.804 --> 00:15:42.730
They're going to vary a little bit.
They're going to be in different languages

00:15:42.755 --> 00:15:46.818
and figure out what the standards
and how to report on them.

00:15:47.526 --> 00:15:49.639
Now this is very logical,

00:15:50.039 --> 00:15:55.016
but this is harder, this is more
complicated than you have to do it.

00:15:55.041 --> 00:15:58.053
And you're going to see
some of that complexity

00:15:58.078 --> 00:16:01.790
but then, in the next slide, I'm going
to show you how to simplify it down.

00:16:02.148 --> 00:16:09.617
So this is a sketch with some
shortcuts here, some oversimplifications,

00:16:09.642 --> 00:16:16.080
but this is basically a picture of the
world of accessibility standards and laws

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:20.785
and policies and reporting as they apply
to content management systems.

00:16:20.810 --> 00:16:23.699
So let me kind of work
from the inside out here.

00:16:24.326 --> 00:16:27.639
So on the right we've got WCAG 2.0,

00:16:28.885 --> 00:16:33.029
still by far the most common standard
around the world

00:16:33.063 --> 00:16:35.360
in terms of countries and regions
that use it,

00:16:35.664 --> 00:16:37.568
US and Canada use it.

00:16:38.335 --> 00:16:42.644
Add to that 12 new criteria for WCAG 2.1.

00:16:43.001 --> 00:16:46.200
So, in case you're tuning in,
or you didn't…

00:16:46.225 --> 00:16:48.356
I want to really emphasize this,

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:55.353
WCAG 2.1 is exactly WCAG 2.0
plus some more criteria

00:16:55.378 --> 00:16:57.183
and the conformance requirement.

00:16:57.207 --> 00:17:02.015
So if you meet WCAG 2.1,
you're meeting WCAG 2.0.

00:17:02.039 --> 00:17:03.864
So that's the first simplification.

00:17:04.759 --> 00:17:10.022
The next layer out is
you'll see EN 301 549.

00:17:10.047 --> 00:17:13.717
That is the European standard.

00:17:13.741 --> 00:17:16.467
The UK after Brexit is still using it,

00:17:17.325 --> 00:17:22.482
and it has more than— usually
people think of it as just WCAG 2.1.

00:17:22.507 --> 00:17:28.941
But for certain types of products like
authoring tool content management systems,

00:17:28.966 --> 00:17:31.759
it has some specific
requirements for those.

00:17:31.784 --> 00:17:34.791
I call them the harmonized
authoring tool criteria

00:17:34.816 --> 00:17:37.590
because you see the circle below,

00:17:37.614 --> 00:17:45.191
US uses very much those same
authoring tool criteria in section 508.

00:17:45.216 --> 00:17:50.971
So… and then finally, ATAG
adds its own more detailed criteria

00:17:50.996 --> 00:17:54.032
and that's the blue bullet
on the left there.

00:17:54.057 --> 00:17:55.874
If you don't see the screen,

00:17:56.279 --> 00:17:59.126
I've described the structure of this.

00:17:59.151 --> 00:18:04.251
And as I mentioned before,
the slides are available at any point.

00:18:04.276 --> 00:18:08.083
This is a complicated graph.
I do have text alternative for it.

00:18:09.125 --> 00:18:11.661
So the point is that

00:18:11.685 --> 00:18:15.004
you could try to figure out all around
the world what everybody's doing,

00:18:15.029 --> 00:18:19.882
but it boils down to these standards:
ATAG, WCAG 2.1.

00:18:19.907 --> 00:18:21.846
If you meet those two standards,

00:18:21.871 --> 00:18:25.864
You're completely covering it for content
management systems anywhere in the world.

00:18:25.889 --> 00:18:27.342
The whole world can use it.

00:18:27.778 --> 00:18:31.015
So, I've done some analysis for you,

00:18:32.749 --> 00:18:36.955
If you want to do less
good stuff for your users,

00:18:36.987 --> 00:18:41.366
you can go and reanalyze the world
and try to cut corners.

00:18:41.391 --> 00:18:47.335
But why not just keep it simple?
WCAG 2.1, ATAG 2.0.

00:18:47.899 --> 00:18:50.203
Now how to report on these?
Some good news.

00:18:50.624 --> 00:18:54.070
Pretty obvious, you can
do an ATAG report for ATAG.

00:18:54.624 --> 00:18:58.908
This one is still—especially in Europe—
and we're on Europe time today.

00:18:59.997 --> 00:19:01.881
It's really not so widely known.

00:19:01.906 --> 00:19:03.328
is there's…

00:19:03.353 --> 00:19:09.403
a lot of people have heard of VPAT, the
Voluntary Product Accessibility Template,

00:19:09.428 --> 00:19:14.089
but still a lot of people you talk to will
say, "Oh, that's a United States thing."

00:19:15.772 --> 00:19:19.811
Since 2017, it's been international.

00:19:19.839 --> 00:19:24.770
It's covered both US
Section 508 and EN 301 549.

00:19:24.795 --> 00:19:32.804
And now as of last year, it covers all
of the standards that are listed here.

00:19:33.146 --> 00:19:36.645
So you don't need to go
and invent a report format.

00:19:37.336 --> 00:19:42.001
You can use this format to report,
not just for the US,

00:19:42.026 --> 00:19:44.564
It continues to do that
as it has always done.

00:19:44.589 --> 00:19:47.632
But now it reports
it's available for the EU.

00:19:50.709 --> 00:19:59.200
So we're gonna look a little bit more at
what to expect in these kinds of reports.

00:20:01.599 --> 00:20:07.198
I believe it may be obvious,
but I will remind folks,

00:20:07.223 --> 00:20:09.596
we're covering a lot of material here.

00:20:09.621 --> 00:20:11.920
We'll definitely allow time
for questions at the end.

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:14.559
And please put those questions in the chat
as we go,

00:20:14.559 --> 00:20:16.459
and we'll allow time for those.

00:20:18.086 --> 00:20:20.638
Certainly within this time period.

00:20:21.752 --> 00:20:23.440
So one thing I want to highlight is,

00:20:23.440 --> 00:20:27.242
you might have noticed that
there were no countries listed on the ATAG.

00:20:27.727 --> 00:20:33.783
So who needs ATAG requirements?

00:20:33.808 --> 00:20:35.085
One answer is nobody.

00:20:35.110 --> 00:20:41.519
No law or regulation directly requires
the authoring tool accessibility guidelines

00:20:41.673 --> 00:20:45.033
that I know of. If somebody knows
differently, please put it in the chat.

00:20:45.907 --> 00:20:50.453
And yet I say that everybody should use
the authoring tool accessibility guidelines

00:20:50.478 --> 00:20:54.785
because they reduce your risk
of an inaccessible website.

00:20:54.810 --> 00:21:00.150
And it's the website that's produced that
has the most scrutiny and the most users

00:21:00.802 --> 00:21:03.927
of anything in this system.

00:21:03.952 --> 00:21:09.878
And so why would you make it hard
for authors to make things accessible

00:21:09.903 --> 00:21:13.020
and then resulting in more bugs
on your websites?

00:21:13.079 --> 00:21:16.694
So it's completely voluntary,
but I think a really good idea.

00:21:16.719 --> 00:21:21.160
So we're going to talk some more about
what are the differences and why that is.

00:21:24.177 --> 00:21:27.470
If you use these two reports,
remember those questions I asked before,

00:21:27.495 --> 00:21:30.616
the questions down the left here,
the key questions of:

00:21:30.902 --> 00:21:34.374
is accessible content allowed possible?

00:21:34.399 --> 00:21:37.865
Is creation of accessible content prompted?

00:21:38.548 --> 00:21:42.896
Is the process of it inclusive?
Is the authoring process inclusive?

00:21:42.921 --> 00:21:50.053
And so this just shows what those
different standards and reports cover.

00:21:51.434 --> 00:21:56.671
The first two columns are
VPAT 2.4 international.

00:21:56.696 --> 00:22:03.467
They cover all three of those requirements.

00:22:04.157 --> 00:22:05.606
The VPAT part of—

00:22:05.637 --> 00:22:10.594
sorry, the WCAG part of VPAT
doesn't cover the prompts,

00:22:10.619 --> 00:22:14.698
and then those harmonized authoring tool
criteria pick up the prompts.

00:22:15.413 --> 00:22:17.895
But I added a second check mark under ATAG

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:24.628
because they just have
more detailed criteria.

00:22:25.841 --> 00:22:29.402
My favorite being prominence of prompts.

00:22:29.436 --> 00:22:38.500
So prompts just need to exist in as far as
the EU and US harmonized accessibility—

00:22:39.318 --> 00:22:41.448
harmonized authoring tool standards.

00:22:41.473 --> 00:22:43.481
ATAG says they need to be prominent.

00:22:43.506 --> 00:22:45.854
They need to be equally prominent
to other things.

00:22:45.879 --> 00:22:48.873
So thumbs up and that. We want that.

00:22:48.898 --> 00:22:51.734
We want to make it easy
for authors to do the right thing.

00:22:52.472 --> 00:22:55.396
I'm not going to drill into this right now.

00:22:55.421 --> 00:22:57.639
But in a moment, I'll show the—

00:22:58.943 --> 00:23:01.882
you know, just one example, you can
see what good prompts would be like.

00:23:03.127 --> 00:23:04.895
Okay, so we've talked about—

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:06.686
so far about the—

00:23:07.527 --> 00:23:09.044
you know, what—

00:23:09.068 --> 00:23:13.208
let's say we're—you, I, a
business owner, an IT director

00:23:13.256 --> 00:23:16.332
is choosing a content management system
and we want to go out and look

00:23:16.356 --> 00:23:19.541
to see that the producers of
those content management systems

00:23:20.802 --> 00:23:24.620
have provided good instructions,
good information about,

00:23:26.604 --> 00:23:30.254
you know, what works and what doesn't
yet in their content management systems.

00:23:30.279 --> 00:23:31.962
Now let's verify that.

00:23:31.987 --> 00:23:35.644
Step two, verify what the content
management system can do.

00:23:38.839 --> 00:23:45.807
I like this as a starting point.
WordPress lists a bunch of VPAT reports.

00:23:45.832 --> 00:23:48.920
Again, that's the voluntary
product accessibility template.

00:23:50.039 --> 00:23:52.066
I'm going to go ahead and follow this link

00:23:52.091 --> 00:23:55.002
because we're going to take
a look at one of these reports.

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:01.702
I think I'm going to need to change
my screen sharing here, I just realized.

00:24:01.727 --> 00:24:11.461
Okay, bear with me while we…
change the sharing.

00:24:13.465 --> 00:24:20.200
Okay. I'm going to check the chat
really sec—for a quick moment and see.

00:24:22.119 --> 00:24:26.254
Actually, can I have an audio of…
is the browser coming through here?

00:24:29.960 --> 00:24:32.759
<v Ahmed>Yes, it is. </v>
<v Mitchell>Thank you. Thanks for confirming that.</v>

00:24:32.784 --> 00:24:37.028
Okay. So I just followed this
https://vpats.wordpress.com

00:24:37.053 --> 00:24:39.905
and it lists a bunch of VPATs.

00:24:41.254 --> 00:24:50.076
The approach that WordPress has taken
is to show VPATs of partners and content.

00:24:50.101 --> 00:24:53.785
And so, I'm just going to
choose the first ones here.

00:24:53.810 --> 00:24:58.185
So the first problem—
the first VPAT is going to have a problem.

00:24:59.857 --> 00:25:04.511
And remember that VPAT 2.something I said,

00:25:05.345 --> 00:25:09.455
first thing we see here, it doesn't
even have the number of the VPAT.

00:25:10.226 --> 00:25:14.367
But this is not VPAT version 2.
This is VPAT version 1.

00:25:14.392 --> 00:25:17.079
This was back when
it was not international.

00:25:17.103 --> 00:25:21.456
It doesn't really even reference
web content accessibility guidelines.

00:25:21.481 --> 00:25:23.380
So that's the first thing
you want to look for.

00:25:23.405 --> 00:25:26.639
And we're going to come
back to, specific VPATs

00:25:26.663 --> 00:25:30.440
and some of the things,
that they should contain.

00:25:30.465 --> 00:25:34.263
I'll start by summarizing them and
we'll kind of switch back and forth between

00:25:34.288 --> 00:25:37.610
looking at the actual documents

00:25:42.027 --> 00:25:46.936
and some of the things
that I would encourage you to look for

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:48.708
when you're evaluating these.

00:25:48.733 --> 00:25:54.786
So the first thing I mentioned
is the VPAT report even complete?

00:25:54.811 --> 00:25:56.631
Does it have the things that it should?

00:25:56.656 --> 00:26:03.456
These days it should always be
at least VPAT version 2.0.

00:26:04.593 --> 00:26:09.712
Because that's the minimum you need
to even cover WCAG 2.0 accurately.

00:26:10.624 --> 00:26:16.448
And if you're using WCAG 2.1, like half
a billion people in Europe need to do,

00:26:18.160 --> 00:26:22.003
it needs to be VPAT version 2.3 or higher.

00:26:22.028 --> 00:26:25.535
So it's up to 2.4 now.
The differences are very slight.

00:26:25.852 --> 00:26:30.272
So if you find, anything,
VPAT 2.3 or higher,

00:26:30.297 --> 00:26:33.982
you're all set for WCAG—to
cover WCAG, you know, accurate,

00:26:34.007 --> 00:26:36.105
well, accurate, that's a separate question.

00:26:36.130 --> 00:26:39.444
It has the right pieces in it
to answer these questions.

00:26:39.801 --> 00:26:44.086
It really must list the name and version
of the product that was tested.

00:26:45.024 --> 00:26:50.078
You know, obviously,
features and bugs and change.

00:26:50.103 --> 00:26:51.839
So if you don't even know what
was tested,

00:26:52.039 --> 00:26:56.348
the reality is it may be
a version old or more,

00:26:56.373 --> 00:27:01.591
but if you know what it is, then you can
triangulate what might be different.

00:27:01.869 --> 00:27:05.683
And specifically for a
content management system product,

00:27:05.708 --> 00:27:10.085
you know, it must actually include
and report on the authoring tool criteria.

00:27:10.110 --> 00:27:16.772
I meant, because, let's just say there's a
varying range of quality of these reports

00:27:16.797 --> 00:27:18.895
and we're going to look
a little bit more about that.

00:27:18.920 --> 00:27:24.034
You know, does it have the just basic
requirements that it needs to contain?

00:27:24.059 --> 00:27:27.407
Next question: is the report credible?

00:27:30.160 --> 00:27:34.758
Does it say what was tested?
Like what was the scope of testing?

00:27:34.783 --> 00:27:38.890
It's normal to test a sample of things
in complex systems.

00:27:38.915 --> 00:27:41.841
Well, what was the sample that was tested?
Was that a reasonable sample?

00:27:41.866 --> 00:27:50.707
You should cover, you know, at
least a core process of logging in,

00:27:51.381 --> 00:27:58.200
choosing accessible-ready templates
and editing content like a block editor.

00:27:58.440 --> 00:28:01.714
You know, if it was missing
one of those core steps,

00:28:01.739 --> 00:28:03.840
well, it shouldn't, right?
First of all,

00:28:03.865 --> 00:28:08.835
and you want to know what it includes
and didn't include in the sampling.

00:28:09.575 --> 00:28:13.999
And we'll look at these next ones
in a little more detail,

00:28:14.024 --> 00:28:19.774
"remarks explaining the ratings."
I'll give a visual of that in a moment.

00:28:19.799 --> 00:28:24.230
This third one, the auditor
is a reputable third party.

00:28:24.255 --> 00:28:27.588
That is, not a minimum.

00:28:28.203 --> 00:28:35.539
That is a, you know, there are companies
that test their own, and do a good job.

00:28:36.735 --> 00:28:44.301
But, you know, if it's a third party
that's named on the VPAT report,

00:28:45.035 --> 00:28:46.855
you know, that both shows independence

00:28:46.880 --> 00:28:48.725
and you can look into that company and say,

00:28:48.750 --> 00:28:52.014
Hey, are they known for doing
a good job on these things?

00:28:52.277 --> 00:28:55.142
I wouldn't say that's a must have,
but that's a bonus.

00:28:55.166 --> 00:28:56.935
It's a plus in terms of credibility,

00:28:56.960 --> 00:29:00.367
especially when you're in a hurry
and who isn't in a hurry, you know?

00:29:02.019 --> 00:29:05.026
So, we're gonna…

00:29:07.407 --> 00:29:10.959
that first one that I mentioned,
what was tested?

00:29:11.713 --> 00:29:13.626
In the case of content management systems,

00:29:13.650 --> 00:29:17.105
not just the functionality of the
content management system itself,

00:29:17.130 --> 00:29:21.356
but what it was creating is important.

00:29:21.381 --> 00:29:23.246
And let me say that,

00:29:23.270 --> 00:29:28.440
if you just stick in "Hello World" or "Lorem
ipsum" into a content management system,

00:29:28.465 --> 00:29:29.932
you really haven't tested it.

00:29:29.956 --> 00:29:34.091
You got to think about what are
the different kinds of content elements

00:29:34.116 --> 00:29:36.174
that are pertinent for accessibility.

00:29:36.199 --> 00:29:40.710
And I know that others, in
this WordPress accessibility Day

00:29:40.735 --> 00:29:42.973
have covered this as well.

00:29:43.528 --> 00:29:49.158
You know, so take this as my perspective
on what are some key kinds of content,

00:29:49.183 --> 00:29:51.598
images, of course, with alt text

00:29:51.623 --> 00:29:55.443
content structure, such as
headings, lists, and tables.

00:29:55.468 --> 00:29:57.685
Don't forget nesting them.

00:29:57.759 --> 00:30:01.082
Interactive elements like
links, buttons, and forms.

00:30:01.107 --> 00:30:04.118
Don't forget error messages of
forms if you use those.

00:30:05.115 --> 00:30:07.908
More complex patterns.
There's many of those

00:30:07.933 --> 00:30:11.360
threaded discussions and menus are a
couple of examples.

00:30:11.385 --> 00:30:13.092
You might contain video.

00:30:13.117 --> 00:30:18.622
Well, the product, the content
management system probably supports video

00:30:18.647 --> 00:30:23.615
and it probably supports
multilingual content.

00:30:25.068 --> 00:30:26.723
One of the things you'll notice here is

00:30:26.747 --> 00:30:29.805
your website might not
include every one of these.

00:30:29.830 --> 00:30:34.071
And so this is where the detail
of the reports can be really helpful

00:30:34.096 --> 00:30:36.869
because it might have a problem with video.

00:30:36.894 --> 00:30:39.890
this particular tool might be
really bad at video.

00:30:39.915 --> 00:30:41.978
You might choose it
anyway, because you say:

00:30:42.002 --> 00:30:47.446
I'm seldom, if ever, going to use video
or I don't need multilingual content.

00:30:47.471 --> 00:30:49.093
I mean, those would be shortcuts.

00:30:49.118 --> 00:30:52.883
You never know, you might get committed
and in the future need those things,

00:30:52.908 --> 00:30:55.065
but at least you can be
a discerning customer.

00:30:56.752 --> 00:31:00.839
So I said that the next one was like,
"Do the ratings match the remarks?"

00:31:00.839 --> 00:31:05.750
So for this, I'm going to bring up—
I'm going to look at Adobe,

00:31:06.242 --> 00:31:11.911
because I worked on these. I did the one
I'm going to show you, I actually wrote.

00:31:11.936 --> 00:31:13.912
although they don't disclose that,
that's fine.

00:31:13.937 --> 00:31:19.745
This is public knowledge
that I'm telling you.

00:31:19.770 --> 00:31:23.094
I know that a lot of consulting
companies keep their clients secret

00:31:23.158 --> 00:31:25.658
and Level Access was no exception.

00:31:27.418 --> 00:31:31.823
But, we were proud to publicly talk
about our partnership with Adobe,

00:31:31.848 --> 00:31:34.309
so no particular secrets here.

00:31:35.491 --> 00:31:39.950
What we're going to look at here,
jump to the WCAG section,

00:31:39.975 --> 00:31:42.410
the web content accessibility guidelines

00:31:42.435 --> 00:31:45.312
part of the VPAT report.

00:31:46.542 --> 00:31:52.336
And just for example, the very first
criterion: 1.1.1 non-text content

00:31:52.361 --> 00:31:55.873
that's talking about
alternative text for images.

00:31:55.898 --> 00:31:58.194
Well, I wrote this,
so of course I think it's great.

00:31:59.365 --> 00:32:04.420
It talks about, for example, this
one is for installed software.

00:32:04.445 --> 00:32:09.371
This was for FrameMaker actually,
which is a content management…

00:32:09.396 --> 00:32:12.353
whether it's a content management
system or not, it's an authoring tool

00:32:12.378 --> 00:32:14.079
and that's what they have in common.

00:32:15.527 --> 00:32:19.543
So ratings and remarks. Now we're
talking, that was the thing I mentioned.

00:32:19.567 --> 00:32:21.400
What about ratings and remarks?

00:32:21.858 --> 00:32:25.408
The rating or conformance level here was
partially supports.

00:32:25.944 --> 00:32:26.990
Now, what does that mean?

00:32:27.034 --> 00:32:30.179
It could be supports,
partially supports, or does not support.

00:32:30.279 --> 00:32:32.948
That's the only three levels we would
report at.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:34.464
But if that's all you said,

00:32:34.488 --> 00:32:37.030
a lot of different things are
going to be partially supports

00:32:37.055 --> 00:32:43.855
That can range from one little bug through
like 40% of all of the websites screwed up.

00:32:43.880 --> 00:32:48.912
So you really need to look at the comment,
the remark for that.

00:32:48.937 --> 00:32:53.897
So the remark is here, most product
functions do not contain images,

00:32:53.921 --> 00:32:56.290
which would require a text alternative,

00:32:56.400 --> 00:32:59.444
but exceptions include…
So what it's saying is

00:32:59.469 --> 00:33:03.313
for the most part, there aren't even any
images in the product where this matters,

00:33:03.338 --> 00:33:05.759
but there's a couple of specific ones.

00:33:05.784 --> 00:33:07.493
Now, right away you can say:

00:33:07.517 --> 00:33:11.979
well, yeah, that sounds like mo…
partially supports, mostly works.

00:33:12.004 --> 00:33:16.518
And you even have detail of like, oh, you
can go and work around those problems

00:33:16.543 --> 00:33:18.448
or, you know, use JAWS scripting
if you had to,

00:33:18.473 --> 00:33:21.126
or, you know, this is useful information.

00:33:21.151 --> 00:33:24.281
But really important
just in terms of order,

00:33:24.306 --> 00:33:30.491
the second one is maybe arguably first in
priority, which is the authored content.

00:33:31.179 --> 00:33:33.054
Also is partially supports. Okay, great.

00:33:33.079 --> 00:33:36.090
Oh, so what can I not do with
authored content?

00:33:36.115 --> 00:33:37.757
Oh, okay. What does that mean?

00:33:37.782 --> 00:33:42.043
Partially supports means I can
only partially put alt text on images.

00:33:42.068 --> 00:33:47.043
Okay, what's going on?
So in here, the case was,

00:33:47.068 --> 00:33:50.400
well authors can provide text
alternative for most images,

00:33:50.400 --> 00:33:54.013
but some image buttons in certain
navigation controls.

00:33:54.038 --> 00:33:58.594
So again, from a point
of view of verify—

00:33:58.619 --> 00:34:03.073
of just making, seeing
if this is even a trustworthy document,

00:34:03.098 --> 00:34:05.669
you want to see that
there's this kind of detail here.

00:34:05.694 --> 00:34:08.895
Now it's going to be very
different detail in different situations.

00:34:08.920 --> 00:34:12.038
But like, is there an explanation for
why they gave that rating?

00:34:12.063 --> 00:34:14.447
Like if there's not, if you look at this
and you're like:

00:34:14.471 --> 00:34:16.616
that doesn't tell me anything,

00:34:16.641 --> 00:34:19.096
it kind of puts the whole report
into question.

00:34:19.121 --> 00:34:22.871
And then if it does tell you, it
makes the report much more credible

00:34:22.896 --> 00:34:26.750
and hopefully actually provides
useful information that you can work with.

00:34:31.234 --> 00:34:35.895
Now there's, you know, 50 WCAG
2.1 criteria,

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:38.320
and you're in a hurry and you want to
compare to,

00:34:39.649 --> 00:34:43.096
you have a product in mind you want to use,
you're in a hurry.

00:34:43.121 --> 00:34:44.335
Where do you start?

00:34:44.360 --> 00:34:48.037
Now all of the criteria are important,
but I like to look at the heavy hitters.

00:34:48.062 --> 00:34:50.180
What do I mean by heavy hitters?

00:34:50.205 --> 00:34:52.895
Criteria that apply the most broadly.

00:34:52.920 --> 00:34:57.295
So like basically every product is going
to have,

00:34:57.320 --> 00:35:03.151
these are going to apply to every page and
screen of every authoring tool

00:35:03.176 --> 00:35:05.075
and the content that it produces.

00:35:05.100 --> 00:35:10.909
So, you know, if you look at these,
this first list,

00:35:10.934 --> 00:35:15.001
and this is like the non-text content,
graphics, we just talked about,

00:35:15.026 --> 00:35:20.639
info and relationships
for structure of HTML.

00:35:20.664 --> 00:35:23.425
I'm going to jump to the fourth one,
name, role, value

00:35:23.449 --> 00:35:26.432
for the structure of interactive elements,

00:35:26.457 --> 00:35:28.167
to this middle one, numerically

00:35:28.191 --> 00:35:34.582
resizing and reflowing text for people with
low vision, especially to enlarge content

00:35:34.607 --> 00:35:37.280
and the keyboard criteria.
There's a list of those.

00:35:37.305 --> 00:35:41.934
So this list right here is
a lot less imposing than,

00:35:41.959 --> 00:35:43.400
you know, the whole list of 50.

00:35:43.480 --> 00:35:47.609
Now, again, the whole list of 50 is
our hard requirements,

00:35:47.634 --> 00:35:52.376
but we're talking about you're opening up
somebody's report and where do you start.

00:35:52.401 --> 00:35:55.035
It actually can be a kind of a…

00:35:55.511 --> 00:35:58.824
you can take a whole day trying to read
from the top to the bottom.

00:35:58.849 --> 00:36:02.039
And I would recommend start
by jumping to these heavy hitters.

00:36:02.760 --> 00:36:05.069
Color criteria are interesting.
They're kind of special

00:36:05.094 --> 00:36:07.812
because for content,
they're super important

00:36:07.836 --> 00:36:10.491
like contrast and use of color.

00:36:10.516 --> 00:36:15.347
But, I just find that for
content management systems, specifically,

00:36:15.372 --> 00:36:20.562
they rarely fail to allow authors to
set colors. I mean, that's what they do.

00:36:20.587 --> 00:36:25.140
So the author is capable of choosing colors
that will conform to contrast.

00:36:25.165 --> 00:36:28.587
But they tend to be pretty bad at
prompting authors to do that.

00:36:28.612 --> 00:36:30.953
So that's kind of a special one.

00:36:31.982 --> 00:36:35.522
Something to watch out for.
I would encourage everybody here,

00:36:35.546 --> 00:36:40.636
to make noise
and ask for a better prompting

00:36:40.660 --> 00:36:44.755
on color in authoring systems

00:36:44.780 --> 00:36:47.944
Now there's a few more
that depend on your content.

00:36:47.969 --> 00:36:51.257
Pre-recorded video has some criteria.

00:36:51.282 --> 00:36:55.747
Multilingual text has
language of page and language of parts.

00:36:55.772 --> 00:36:57.570
Error messages, if you
have them, have those.

00:36:57.594 --> 00:36:59.429
and I think those are all quite important.

00:36:59.454 --> 00:37:02.000
Those are my next level of heavy hitters.

00:37:02.039 --> 00:37:05.335
Again, I can't repeat enough.
They're all required.

00:37:05.360 --> 00:37:09.825
The purpose of this is to say,
I want to skim a report

00:37:09.850 --> 00:37:11.524
and see what it tells me.

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:17.866
For that purpose, this skim, you know,
somewhere between 14 and 22 out of the 50

00:37:17.891 --> 00:37:21.646
will give you a very
good first, first cut at reading a report.

00:37:25.239 --> 00:37:28.565
And now what about those extra
authoring tool criteria?

00:37:28.590 --> 00:37:30.582
So I've already summarized them

00:37:30.607 --> 00:37:32.939
and we're not going to drill
down into every one of them.

00:37:33.417 --> 00:37:35.075
But just, this is what to look for.

00:37:38.064 --> 00:37:39.148
I call them harmonized.

00:37:39.172 --> 00:37:44.711
Harmonized means that different standards
try to be pretty similar.

00:37:44.736 --> 00:37:48.171
So the US section 508 has
a prompts requirement.

00:37:48.196 --> 00:37:50.840
It's harder to see that
in the EU requirements.

00:37:51.079 --> 00:37:54.710
It calls it guide the production of
content—of accessible content.

00:37:54.735 --> 00:37:58.293
Guide—I'm sorry,
guide the production of accessible content.

00:38:00.673 --> 00:38:03.575
It also has a—it breaks out the templates,

00:38:05.257 --> 00:38:07.873
to say that
they're identified as templates.

00:38:08.508 --> 00:38:12.480
Both of them also put a requirement
on the product documentation,

00:38:12.480 --> 00:38:19.600
which, I will say, is a shortcut
that you might find,

00:38:19.957 --> 00:38:23.368
unfortunately that might not just
even get reported.

00:38:25.217 --> 00:38:28.121
But the product documentation
needs to highlight

00:38:28.146 --> 00:38:31.470
what are the accessibility
capabilities of the product.

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:38.211
And I mentioned before, that my favorite
being the prominence requirement of ATAG.

00:38:38.236 --> 00:38:39.966
That's a plus. That's a…

00:38:40.601 --> 00:38:44.441
The ATAG guideline B has
several more detailed criteria

00:38:44.466 --> 00:38:51.566
that mesh very well with the US and EU
and global standards for authoring tools

00:38:51.591 --> 00:38:53.228
and content management systems.

00:38:53.253 --> 00:38:56.832
And it just adds more detail to some
such as prominence.

00:38:58.474 --> 00:39:05.849
So, you know, whenever possible,
you know, ask for, and then scrutinize

00:39:05.874 --> 00:39:09.548
whether the product is doing that.

00:39:09.573 --> 00:39:11.857
We are nearing our time. So
I'm going have to run through,

00:39:11.882 --> 00:39:14.000
our time for questions, I should say.

00:39:14.025 --> 00:39:16.944
We're going to allow almost
10 minutes for questions.

00:39:16.969 --> 00:39:19.070
So we're going to go a little faster here.

00:39:21.967 --> 00:39:23.197
Test it yourself.

00:39:23.844 --> 00:39:26.239
Hopefully you've got a report
so you don't have to test everything.

00:39:26.273 --> 00:39:28.613
You can spot check and just reality check.

00:39:29.058 --> 00:39:30.489
Why do I say that?

00:39:31.306 --> 00:39:35.010
Because it's easy to exaggerate
even a well-written report.

00:39:35.035 --> 00:39:37.906
I've seen this happen.
Boy, this was a great report.

00:39:37.931 --> 00:39:40.414
They're so proud of their accessibility,

00:39:40.439 --> 00:39:43.339
but like it was an authoring tool,
it was really hard to use.

00:39:43.364 --> 00:39:46.760
It was like, oh, I guess you can
do that. But wow, that was hard.

00:39:47.039 --> 00:39:50.991
So, you know, like any
marketing claims, you know,

00:39:52.149 --> 00:39:54.918
go and test it. But at least,
you know what the claim is,

00:39:54.943 --> 00:39:57.814
you're not starting from a blank slate.

00:39:58.211 --> 00:40:01.207
And again, I'm just want to emphasize
the importance of these prompts,

00:40:01.232 --> 00:40:04.599
especially if you have
a bunch of content authors,

00:40:04.840 --> 00:40:07.562
I mean, there's no way you're going to
create an accessible website

00:40:07.586 --> 00:40:08.639
without good prompting.

00:40:09.039 --> 00:40:10.802
It's just makes it too hard.

00:40:11.310 --> 00:40:13.961
So test those prompts yourself, see if the…

00:40:13.986 --> 00:40:18.612
and others in this series of
WordPress Accessibility Day

00:40:18.637 --> 00:40:20.842
have really shown you how to do that.

00:40:21.716 --> 00:40:23.392
Here's an example of good prompts.

00:40:23.417 --> 00:40:25.719
For those who are developing content
management systems,

00:40:25.719 --> 00:40:30.399
do take a look at Microsoft's
accessibility checker built into Office.

00:40:30.424 --> 00:40:36.693
It is prominent. It's level
as the spell checker now.

00:40:36.718 --> 00:40:38.412
You can leave it on all the time.

00:40:38.436 --> 00:40:41.682
It's great. That's what all
content management systems should do.

00:40:42.832 --> 00:40:45.918
So I'm going to anticipate
a couple of your questions.

00:40:45.943 --> 00:40:47.288
Okay. So just tell me:

00:40:47.312 --> 00:40:50.727
"What are the best content
management systems for accessibility?"

00:40:50.752 --> 00:40:53.014
What are they? It's WordPress, right?

00:40:53.816 --> 00:40:55.468
I'm not going to answer that.

00:40:55.899 --> 00:40:59.419
This is like in <i>2001: A Space Odyssey</i>,
saying:

00:40:59.452 --> 00:41:01.321
"HAL, please open the pod bay doors."

00:41:01.346 --> 00:41:03.910
And HAL says:
"I'm sorry, Dave, I can't do that."

00:41:04.252 --> 00:41:08.271
I'm sorry, I can't tell you exactly what
the best content management systems are.

00:41:08.501 --> 00:41:10.921
Not because I'm trying to kill you
in outer space.

00:41:11.264 --> 00:41:13.501
Because none of them is perfect

00:41:13.526 --> 00:41:17.213
and what's going to work best
is going to vary by your needs.

00:41:17.491 --> 00:41:21.451
So I've listed some links here,
download the slides.

00:41:21.484 --> 00:41:23.962
I'll give you the link for that
in a moment here.

00:41:25.303 --> 00:41:27.475
And, I'm just going
to highlight one of these.

00:41:27.500 --> 00:41:29.773
This one in the middle: TextBox Digital.

00:41:30.152 --> 00:41:34.092
Some folks in the UK have this.
This helps…

00:41:34.116 --> 00:41:37.658
you can filter it by content
management systems

00:41:37.683 --> 00:41:41.096
and find their accessibility statements.
It's really cool.

00:41:41.121 --> 00:41:42.140
Come back to that.

00:41:43.454 --> 00:41:47.865
This is more for future… I was not going
to go over this in any case in detail,

00:41:47.890 --> 00:41:52.481
but if you are a buyer, it's a great
idea to have a procurement policy,

00:41:52.703 --> 00:41:54.486
not just for content management systems,

00:41:54.510 --> 00:41:58.894
but for any software or websites
that you hire or buy,

00:41:59.172 --> 00:42:02.584
and some great resources,
plentiful resources on the internet

00:42:02.609 --> 00:42:03.911
to say how to set up your—

00:42:04.967 --> 00:42:09.133
how to make sure that
you invest in the right ways.

00:42:10.123 --> 00:42:15.000
And then, on the vendor side, those who
create the content management systems,

00:42:15.798 --> 00:42:18.814
you know, these statements that we talked
about, here's how to make them.

00:42:21.309 --> 00:42:24.257
And still you say,
ah, this is so much Mitchell,

00:42:24.282 --> 00:42:26.971
but I need a content management
system right now!

00:42:26.996 --> 00:42:28.116
Tell me the minimum.

00:42:28.925 --> 00:42:33.007
Well, first I'll say, you know,
don't skip it entirely because

00:42:33.032 --> 00:42:36.167
do you really need it so soon that
you're willing to choose the wrong one?

00:42:36.548 --> 00:42:39.531
I, yeah—
so there's the challenging question.

00:42:39.556 --> 00:42:42.780
Take a breath, choose the right system.

00:42:42.805 --> 00:42:44.519
And if you could only check one thing,

00:42:44.519 --> 00:42:47.710
if I could do this, I would say,

00:42:47.735 --> 00:42:49.990
take a website that was produced by that

00:42:50.023 --> 00:42:53.538
and have a person who really uses
screen readers well, check it out.

00:42:54.046 --> 00:42:56.447
And choose a website that's like
what you want to make.

00:42:56.920 --> 00:43:01.006
If it can't do that,
yeah, you need to ask more questions.

00:43:03.006 --> 00:43:04.656
I'm going to end with these thoughts.

00:43:06.798 --> 00:43:11.055
Is a fully conformant
CMS possible? I say…

00:43:11.104 --> 00:43:12.711
yes, that's possible.

00:43:12.736 --> 00:43:14.851
And here's a thought provoking question:

00:43:15.336 --> 00:43:16.812
Is "how to do that?"

00:43:18.796 --> 00:43:22.564
And I say, together we can do that.

00:43:22.589 --> 00:43:25.207
That's what this whole community
is going to do together

00:43:25.232 --> 00:43:27.040
by being demanding customers,

00:43:27.675 --> 00:43:31.182
by the dedication that
the Core WordPress team

00:43:31.207 --> 00:43:33.584
and other vendors are putting into this.

00:43:34.865 --> 00:43:38.031
We just keep working at it,
keep asking these "how" questions.

00:43:38.119 --> 00:43:40.400
"How" is the right question until we get
this done.

00:43:41.840 --> 00:43:46.661
So with that, we are a couple minutes
into the content—into the questions

00:43:46.686 --> 00:43:50.397
We do have, if I'm not mistaken,
six more minutes for questions.

00:43:50.422 --> 00:43:53.761
We'll get some here and we'll make
sure that they all get answered later.

00:43:53.786 --> 00:43:55.262
Thank you.

00:43:56.880 --> 00:43:58.265
<v Ahmed> Thank you so much, Mitchell.

00:43:58.290 --> 00:44:00.822
That was an insightful presentation.

00:44:01.815 --> 00:44:04.638
We all learned a lot today.

00:44:04.663 --> 00:44:10.406
I'm sure the community itself, the
organizers, stakeholders out there,

00:44:10.431 --> 00:44:13.323
people who want to
learn about accessibility,

00:44:13.347 --> 00:44:17.342
was able to take away
a lot of big points out of this.

00:44:17.905 --> 00:44:22.421
So, we will begin the
question and answer session.

00:44:22.446 --> 00:44:24.774
We have five or six questions.

00:44:24.799 --> 00:44:25.862
So the first one:

00:44:27.298 --> 00:44:31.710
What are your recommendations to
the community building WordPress

00:44:31.734 --> 00:44:33.316
to be more accessible?

00:44:39.348 --> 00:44:42.362
<v Mitchell> I will say, I should have
given you a couple of disclaimers upfront.

00:44:42.387 --> 00:44:44.474
One is that I am not a WordPress expert.

00:44:44.499 --> 00:44:49.064
So I'm going to answer that in
a more general way.

00:44:51.562 --> 00:44:55.373
And I'll—it's a little bit of a
repeat of what I said, which is,

00:44:55.398 --> 00:44:59.825
you know, I think that prompting for
authors, prompting for content creators,

00:45:00.738 --> 00:45:02.468
Like if you do that well,

00:45:02.888 --> 00:45:05.031
that's the first thing to do well.

00:45:07.086 --> 00:45:11.453
I would say that…

00:45:11.478 --> 00:45:12.517
I'm tempted to…

00:45:12.548 --> 00:45:17.189
it's a hard— it's a close second though,
to make the interface itself accessible.

00:45:17.214 --> 00:45:19.709
And it's not just to meet the requirements,

00:45:20.074 --> 00:45:24.960
but to make the actual authoring experience
rock solid for people with disabilities.

00:45:25.400 --> 00:45:28.138
There's two great things
that happen when you do that.

00:45:28.177 --> 00:45:32.000
One is you help solve the employment gap.

00:45:32.599 --> 00:45:36.320
People with disabilities around the world
are today,

00:45:36.781 --> 00:45:39.119
you know, statistics are shockingly
consistent

00:45:39.119 --> 00:45:42.956
that they're like employed less than half
the rate of people without disabilities

00:45:43.448 --> 00:45:45.927
and the digital world can solve that.

00:45:45.952 --> 00:45:47.332
But another great way—

00:45:47.357 --> 00:45:51.927
another great reason to want to make
your authoring experience accessible

00:45:52.221 --> 00:45:56.870
is that then you've got
people with disabilities,

00:45:57.283 --> 00:46:02.199
both authoring and checking the results of
their authoring.

00:46:02.441 --> 00:46:05.281
And so you've got a really great
community feedback loop

00:46:05.646 --> 00:46:08.787
to tell you not only how to make
your authoring process better,

00:46:08.812 --> 00:46:10.159
but how to make
the output better.

00:46:10.159 --> 00:46:13.756
You've got more people with disabilities
scrutinizing that output.

00:46:13.781 --> 00:46:16.742
So that's a fairly broad
kind of philosophical answer.

00:46:18.163 --> 00:46:20.558
And like I said, I'm not
actually the WordPress expert.

00:46:20.583 --> 00:46:25.509
I want to take a step back and put
WordPress in the context of authoring tools

00:46:25.534 --> 00:46:27.320
and content management systems in general.

00:46:28.295 --> 00:46:32.452
<v Ahmed> I agree with you Mitchell,
but you did mention that it's a community

00:46:32.477 --> 00:46:34.468
and we should make changes together.

00:46:34.493 --> 00:46:37.895
which is why your comment
does make an impact.

00:46:37.920 --> 00:46:42.817
And it's adding value to initiatives
such as WP Accessibility Day.

00:46:42.842 --> 00:46:44.341
So the next
question,

00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:48.895
how can we sell the idea or even educate
our leadership

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:52.474
on leads to make
accessibility a top priority?

00:46:55.173 --> 00:46:57.090
<v Mitchell> There's many
answers to that question

00:46:57.114 --> 00:47:00.183
and I will just hit a
couple of high points.

00:47:02.512 --> 00:47:05.326
I probably— everybody on—

00:47:05.351 --> 00:47:07.979
one answer is watch
all of the presentations

00:47:08.004 --> 00:47:09.559
for WordPress Accessibility Day,

00:47:09.559 --> 00:47:11.546
because I think
that's just a theme throughout.

00:47:12.642 --> 00:47:14.118
And,

00:47:16.236 --> 00:47:21.034
I mean, the best way is because you're…

00:47:21.194 --> 00:47:23.083
you care about users in general,

00:47:23.108 --> 00:47:26.567
you care about your customers.
You want to have more customers.

00:47:26.592 --> 00:47:28.722
You don't want to slap
your customers in the face

00:47:28.747 --> 00:47:30.843
when they come wanting to use your content.

00:47:31.343 --> 00:47:35.826
So whenever you can think about it
in terms of a user-centered approach,

00:47:36.327 --> 00:47:39.633
If your company culture
is already thinking about your users.

00:47:39.658 --> 00:47:43.309
These are your users.
That's always the best way to start.

00:47:44.182 --> 00:47:48.159
If that doesn't get their
attention, you know,

00:47:48.679 --> 00:47:52.819
go back to the slides with the
complex rules around the world

00:47:52.844 --> 00:47:58.734
and the requirements and
the legislation and the lawsuits

00:47:58.759 --> 00:48:00.107
and scare them a little bit.

00:48:00.147 --> 00:48:03.305
But then once you've scared them,
come back to doing the right thing.

00:48:03.330 --> 00:48:04.998
Don't just think about laws all the time.

00:48:05.022 --> 00:48:08.037
Just, that's the reason to
begin doing the right thing.

00:48:08.062 --> 00:48:11.039
And then come back to that first
question. What can we do for the users?

00:48:12.519 --> 00:48:14.817
<v Ahmed> Absolutely. Next question:

00:48:14.842 --> 00:48:18.154
Imagine you don't know
anything about WordPress

00:48:18.179 --> 00:48:22.360
and checking its VPAT. Would
you consider using it as a CMS?

00:48:23.804 --> 00:48:25.939
<v Mitchell> So, I have not.

00:48:25.964 --> 00:48:28.388
So somebody please ping me if there is one.

00:48:28.419 --> 00:48:34.767
I have not seen, like WordPress
core having its own VPAT report.

00:48:35.353 --> 00:48:37.212
So I'm going to answer
it a little differently,

00:48:37.237 --> 00:48:41.972
looking at WordPress's
accessibility statements,

00:48:41.997 --> 00:48:45.275
which I just had one link in there,
just in the interest of time.

00:48:45.300 --> 00:48:47.772
I just said, here,
this is the start here page,

00:48:47.804 --> 00:48:51.995
but as many others on this series
have talked about

00:48:52.020 --> 00:48:56.719
and really drilling down into choosing
the accessibility-ready templates,

00:48:56.880 --> 00:49:00.081
developing your own templates,
watching out for the plugins,

00:49:00.106 --> 00:49:02.183
you know, it's got just
a ton of information there.

00:49:02.208 --> 00:49:04.064
It says what works and what doesn't.

00:49:04.089 --> 00:49:08.634
It really comes across as very transparent,

00:49:08.659 --> 00:49:12.269
and honest about what works
and what doesn't.

00:49:12.294 --> 00:49:15.173
It tells you exactly how to
go and find the known issues.

00:49:15.198 --> 00:49:20.480
So, you know, at a glance, I say it has,
you know, has what we're looking for.

00:49:22.808 --> 00:49:26.575
One other thing I flew by and—
so these are sort of—

00:49:26.911 --> 00:49:29.480
I guess I have to say that I haven't gone
and done

00:49:29.519 --> 00:49:32.800
the same level of deep verification
for WordPress

00:49:32.840 --> 00:49:35.224
that I listed that each of us should do.

00:49:36.959 --> 00:49:44.205
And that still hasn't been done
in years anyway, like,

00:49:45.245 --> 00:49:51.279
I know the Gutenberg block editor
got a detailed audit,

00:49:51.304 --> 00:49:52.779
taking a look at that.

00:49:53.800 --> 00:49:56.628
Oh, so there's an example.
I did take a look at that piece of it

00:49:56.653 --> 00:50:04.523
and, well, yeah, I mean, it was audited by
a very well-known and reputable third party

00:50:04.548 --> 00:50:08.869
and I could see that
it covered the different pieces,

00:50:08.894 --> 00:50:12.772
you know, the different requirements well,
including the prompting pretty well.

00:50:13.321 --> 00:50:15.936
So yeah, I mean,
there's a lot to like about WordPress,

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:20.783
and it lets you know where the problems are
and you can work around them

00:50:20.808 --> 00:50:25.639
work around them and, you know,
upvote them as well, you know,

00:50:27.265 --> 00:50:28.932
yeah, that's how I'll answer. Yeah.

00:50:28.957 --> 00:50:33.091
<v Ahmed> Thank you so much, Mitchell.
I would have loved to continue the Q and A,

00:50:33.116 --> 00:50:36.543
but we are out of time.
So thank you so much once again.

00:50:36.568 --> 00:50:40.202
I would encourage you to
post your answers on our website,

00:50:40.227 --> 00:50:44.335
so that the questions that are posted,
that can also be addressed.

00:50:44.360 --> 00:50:48.194
On that note,
we come to the end of the session:

00:50:48.219 --> 00:50:52.931
If it's true, it ain't bragging.
Choosing a CMS for accessibility.

